quran[25]{c,v,t,f}:
  76,26,"and prostrate yourself before Him at night, and extol His Glory during the long watches of the night.{1}",footnotes:1:[The rule followed in the Quran is that wherever the]
  76,27,"Verily they love (the good of this world) that is hastily obtainable and are oblivious of the burdensome Day ahead of them.{1}",footnotes:1:[That is, the reason why the disbelieving Quraish still]
  76,28,"We created them and strengthened their joints; and whenever We wish, We can change their faces entirely.{1}",footnotes:1:[The sentence, “And when We will, We can replace]
  76,29,"Verily this is an Exhortation; so let him who so will take a way to his Lord."
  76,30,"But your willing shall be of no avail until Allah Himself so wills.{1} Surely Allah is All-Knowing, Most Wise.",footnotes:1:[Three things have been said in these verses:]
  76,31,"He admits to His Mercy whomsoever He pleases. As for the wrong-doers, He has prepared for them a grievous chastisement.{1}",footnotes:1:[In this verse “wrongdoers” imply the people whom the]
  77,1,"By the (winds) sent forth in quick succession,"
  77,2,"which then blow tempestuously"
  77,3,"and raise (clouds) and scatter them around,"
  77,4,"then winnow them thoroughly,"
  77,5,"and then cast (Allah's) remembrance (in people's hearts),"
  77,6,"to serve as an excuse or a warning.{1}",footnotes:1:[That is, sometimes the failure of winds causes the people to be alarmed at the prospect of a famine, and they turn to Allah to repent of their sins. Sometimes they bring a lot of rain and the people turn to Allah in gratitude, and sometimes their blowing violently causes dread in the hearts and the people turn to Allah from fear of destruction.]
  77,7,"Surely what you are promised{1} shall come to pass. {2}",footnotes:1:[Another meaning can be: That which you are being threatened with, i.e. the Resurrection and Hereafter.],footnotes:2:[Here an oath has been sworn by five things on the inevitability of the Resurrection:]
  77,8,"So when the stars are extinguished,{1}",footnotes:1:[That is, when they lose their light and luster.]
  77,9,"and the sky is rent asunder,{1}",footnotes:1:[When the heaven is rent asunder: when the system and discipline of the heavens under which every star and planet is established and moving in its orbit and everything in the universe is adhering to the bounds set for it]
  77,10,"and the mountains are blown away,"
  77,11,"and the appointed time to bring the Messengers together arrives,(then shall the promised event come to pass).{1}",footnotes:1:[At several places in the Quran it has been stated that when the case of mankind will be presented before Allah on the Day of Resurrection]
  77,12,"To which Day has this task been deferred?"
  77,13,"To the Day of Judgement."
  77,14,"What do you know what the Day of Judgement is?"
  77,15,"Woe on that Day to those that give the lie to the Truth!{1}",footnotes:1:[Deniers: those people who took the news of the coming of Resurrection as a lie]
  77,16,"Did We not destroy many a nation of the earlier times?{1}",footnotes:1:[This is an argument from history for the Hereafter]
  77,17,"And We shall cause those of later times{1} to follow them.",footnotes:1:[That is, this is a permanent law with Us. Just as denial of the Hereafter has proved disastrous for the nations of the past so it will always prove disastrous also for the nations of the future. No nation has been an exception to it before nor will any be so in the future.]
  77,18,"Thus do We deal with the guilty."
  77,19,"Woe on that Day to those that give the lie to the Truth!{1}",footnotes:1:[This sentence in the present context means: The fate they have met or will meet in the world]
